SIMPLE: twit
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Twit
<hw>Twit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Twitted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Twitting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>atwiten</ets>, AS.
<ets>⟦ae⟧tw⟦imac⟧tan</ets> to reproach, blame; <ets>aet</ets> at +
<ets>w⟦imac⟧tan</ets> to reproach, blame; originally, to observe, see,
hence, to observe what is wrong (cf. the meanings of E.
<ets>animadvert</ets>; akin to G. ver<ets>weisen</ets> to censure, OHG.
fir<ets>w⟦imac⟧zan</ets>, Goth. fra<ets>weitan</ets> to avenge, L.
<ets>videre</ets> to see. See <er>Vision</er>, <er>Wit</er>.]</ety>
<def>To vex by bringing to notice, or reminding of, a fault, defect,
misfortune, or the like; to revile; to reproach; to upbraid; to taunt;
<as>as, he <ex>twitted</ex> his friend of falsehood</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This these scoffers <qex>twitted</qex> the Christians with.</q>
<rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Aesop minds men of their errors, without <qex>twitting</qex> them
for what is amiss.</q> <rj><qau>L'Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Twitch</ent>⟦br⟧
